entry.title: [Extensions] Enable tabCapture with workers and offscreen documents
entry.content:
MediaStreams are unavailable in ServiceWorker contexts. This means

the tabCapture API doesn't work in Manifest V3 background contexts

(since these are service worker-based). The primary alternative to

functionality that's tied to a DOM or Window context is to use

offscreen documents; however, these (by design) do not have access

to extension APIs, which means they can't access the tabCapture API.

This effectively means there's no good way to use the tabCapture

API in a background context in Manifest V3.



Fix this by:

- Allowing service worker contexts to use

`tabCapture.getMediaStreamId()`. This returns an ID that can

later be used to fetch a media stream, rather than returning the

MediaStream object itself. As such, it's (conceptually)

compatible with service worker contexts.

- Allowing offscreen documents to use the media stream ID to

start capture via the navigator.getUserMedia() API (which is

what tabCapture.capture() already used).



In practice, this entails allowing extension contexts to use a

media stream generated by another context *on the same origin*, rather

than restricting it to the same frame that created the stream ID.

(This isn't a change in security or privacy, since the extension could

already pass any of this information between its own contexts.)

Additionally, update `tabCapture.getMediaStreamId()`'s implementation

to not rely on the presence of a RenderFrame.



Add an end-to-end test using offscreen documents to capture the

stream of an active tab.

entry.title: [iOS] Autofill Branding refactor
entry.content:
This is an attempt to refactor the existing autofill branding code.



1. Moved files into a separate directory

2. Uses the mediator/coordinator/VC architecture instead of using the

form_input_accessory_view_controller as a sort of coordinator

3. The view BrandingViewController used to be the branding icon. Now it

becomes a wrapper of the icon, so the the view controller could

encapsulate the logic to manage the branding visibility, instead of

taking care of them in the form accessories view controller.

4. Monotone images are removed as we don't support monotone branding

anymore.



The behavior of the branding has also tweaked a bit. Previously, if

autofill becomes not supported DURING the time the keyboard is visible,

the branding would disappear on the spot. As this scenario doesn't

happen (autofill of any type is disabled in Settings, and the user has

to dismiss the keyboard to go there), now the visibility of the branding

is only calculated when the keyboard is about to appear.

entry.title: Add content analysis test for system print from Print Preview
entry.content:
Introduce an extra test to verify content analysis behavior for case

where system print is invoked from the Print Preview dialog.



This could have up to two print dialogs displayed for the user, but

both are for the same original document.



Extend TestPrintViewManagerForContentAnalysis so that tracking PrintJob

destruction is possible. This helps to ensure clean shutdown at test

termination, and also makes it possible to know when it is safe to do

final expectation checks when content analysis allows printing for the

in-browser (non-OOPPD) case.



This test shows that depending upon the platform there could be one or

entry.title: ipcz: Clean up Get() API
entry.content:
This changes how IPCZ_GET_PARTIAL behaves. Data is still copied out of

the parcel as the caller's supplied buffer capacity allows, but the

parcel's own data contents are no longer consumed by the operation: a

subsequent Get() on the same parcel with the same output buffer size

will see the same data. Copied handles are still consumed by the call.



Additionally a Get() on a portal will now always dequeue its parcel

even if it wasn't fully consumed by the call. This simplifies the

implementation and specified behavior slightly.



With the new IPCZ_GET_PARTIAL behavior, a caller can dequeue a parcel

and simultaneously acquire a handle to it without affecting its

contents. This renders IPCZ_GET_PARCEL_ONLY redundant and it is

therefore removed here.

extension which will install Select to Speak's context menu and plumbing

to send the context menu clicks back to Ash via crosapi.

entry.content:
Through TabObserve.onUrlUpdated & onTitleUpdated, we already observed

InvalidateTypes.Title and Url changes. This CL adds other types

observation, i.e: InvalidateTypes.Load and InvalidateTypes.Tab.



This CL is a speculative fix to back press refactor change as

flags in order to observe the differences and avoid potential

performance cost.

entry.title: ipcz: Transaction identifiers for BeginPut() and EndPut()
entry.content:
To support overlapping two-phase puts, EndPut() uses the transaction's

data address as a stable identifier for the specific transaction to be

terminated.



This is not ideal since some transactions have no data associated with

them (and we have to fabricate an address), and two-phase gets would

have a similar problem. We'll want some semantic consistency between the

two APIs, so we should stabilize around something cleaner.



This change introduces a new opaque identifier type, IpczTransaction,

and uses it as a lightweight transaction reference to be output by

BeginPut() and consumed by EndPut(). No behavioral changes otherwise.



A follow-up change will do something similar for BeginGet() and

EndGet() while adding support for overlapping transactions.

entry.title: Reset service worker idle timer by websocket activities
entry.content:
This is done by two steps. The first step let DOMWebsocket notify

ExecutionContext when selected activity happens. The second step let

ServiceWorkerGlobalScope reset idle timer when received such a notice.



Call it notify instead of on... event has two reasons: 1) To indicate

what does the ExecutionContext do with should not affect WebSocket; 2)

At this point there is no need to distinguish different activity yet.

The purpose is to simply notify something happened in the web socket.

What happened is not a concern, for now.



ChromeContentRendererClient implements the logic that limits this

notification to extension service workers.

entry.title: Serialize and compute non-finite color channels
entry.content:
http://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/issues/8629

http://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/39137/files

http://wpt.fyi/results/css/css-color/parsing



Color parsing is a part of Interop 2023. Handling non-finite inputs

to color channels is a bit tricky. At parse time `calc(NaN)` and

`calc(infinity)` (and their equivalents) are valid CSS numerical inputs,

and should get re-serialized as such so that they round-trip.



Per-spec, `calc(NaN)` should become 0 at computed value time.

`calc(infinity)` should remain `calc(infinity)`, except in cases where it represents a clamped color channel, such as lightness or chroma.

Unfortunately, blink had previously made no distinction between parsed

and computed colors, hence the creation of

blink::Color::ResolveNonFiniteValues (called from

TextLinkColors::ColorFromCSSValue) in this CL.



Before CSS Color 4, color functions were less exposed to things like

`calc` functions, so this problem went unnoticed.
